The Adamawa/Taraba Operations Office of the National Emergency Management Agency (NEMA), has embarked on sensitization to flood prone Communities, where they were advised to take precautionary measures in addressing the anticipated flood. Head of Operation for the two states, Mr Iliya Midala during the tour of Communities in Numan, Yola-North and Yola-South, Demsa and lamurde LGAs, along the bank of river Benue told them to observed caution. Midala said, the visits to the area considered to be low and high risk areas, was to raise awareness on the excessive flooding expected in the state as predicted by Nimet and other agencies. He told the people to be vigilant, while urging them to consider option of relocation to the hinterlands for safety where necessary. “Residents of the flood prone areas should always be on red alert as flood can come anytime” he urged. The agency with the support of the grassroots he pointed out, would soon form emergency vanguard in flood communities to enlightened the populace on safety and  precautionary measures. Chairmen of the local councils visited assured NEMA of their administration commitments to step down the awareness to mitigate the challenge of the anticipated  flood. The LGAs visited are s among 275 local government areas across the 36 states of the federation that  fall within the moderately probable flood risk areas, while the remaining 397 local government areas fall within the low probable flood risk areas. The state had been experiencing yearly occurrence of perennial flood due to indiscriminate release of water from the Lagdo Dam from the republic of Cameroon 